But if, said the, as this mandat assumes, the re- presentative is simply to obey the orders of his con- stituents or Caucus whenever he receives thern, there should never henceforth be any dissolution, nor general election3 for it would be sufficient then to appoint deputies who should sit until death or dis- obedience put an end to their deputyship.

To this 1 objected that in such case all debate in Parliament were entirely useless; since no member might vote according to his convictions, but only upon the orders of his masters in that behalf.
